  "summary": "In a confrontation, David rebukes Francis and others for treating Rosalind as a \"money tree.\" He reveals that while Rosalind can use the income from her assets, she cannot touch the principal and must pay approximately £1,906 in income tax. David accuses the group of mocking and hating Rosalind behind her back while begging her for money. Francis responds by stating she hates David for living off his sister, despite David's claim that he is protecting Rosalind from greedy people. Francis exits through a floor-to-ceiling window after issuing a vague threat.\n\nFollowing the argument, David warns a terrified Rosalind that several people are eager to see her dead. He promises to protect her from threats, including the De Guise family, but urges her to be careful if he is not present. David also notes that Rosalind’s sense of conscience may complicate their future.\n\nIn a separate scene, Lynn asks Rolly for a five-hundred-pound loan to help her mother, Adela, who has borrowed money from David Hunter. Rolly refuses, citing his own financial struggles with a new tractor and government bureaucracy. He suggests that Rosalind should help the others since Gordon died without a will. Lynn expresses resentment toward David, whom she believes has Rosalind under his thumb. Meanwhile, Adela reveals she used a check from Rosalind to pay off debts to Arthur, Boddaghan, and Nabvors, expressing relief at being debt-free despite Lynn's bitterness regarding their continued reliance on Rosalind.",
